# Google Slides Variable Replacer

Here's a complete Google Apps Script solution. It uses a web app form where you can input text, then it finds and replaces placeholder variables in your Slides file.

## Setup Approach

I'll give you two options:
1. **Simple version** — replace a single variable
2. **Flexible version** — a web form with multiple variables

---

## Option 1: Simple Version (Single Variable)

This uses `replaceAllText()`, the built-in method for find/replace in Slides.

```javascript
function replaceVariable() {
  // Your Slides file ID (from the URL)
  const presentationId = 'YOUR_PRESENTATION_ID_HERE';

  // The placeholder you're searching for (e.g. {{name}})
  const variable = '{{name}}';

  // The replacement text
  const replacementText = 'John Smith';

  const presentation = SlidesApp.openById(presentationId);
  presentation.replaceAllText(variable, replacementText);
}
```

---

## Option 2: Web App With a Form (Recommended)

This creates a web page with a form. Whatever you type gets replaced into the Slides file.

### Step 1: Create the script (`Code.gs`)

```javascript
// Serves the HTML form
function doGet() {
  return HtmlService.createHtmlOutputFromFile('Form')
    .setTitle('Slides Variable Replacer');
}

// Called by the form when submitted
function replaceVariables(formData) {
  const presentationId = 'YOUR_PRESENTATION_ID_HERE';
  const presentation = SlidesApp.openById(presentationId);

  // formData is an object like { variable: '{{name}}', replacement: 'John' }
  const variable = formData.variable;
  const replacementText = formData.replacement;

  // Replace all instances (the 'true' makes it case-sensitive; remove for case-insensitive)
  presentation.replaceAllText(variable, replacementText, true);

  return 'Replaced all instances of "' + variable + '" with "' + replacementText + '".';
}
```

### Step 2: Create the HTML form (`Form.html`)

In the Apps Script editor, click **+ → HTML** and name it `Form`.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <base target="_top">
    <style>
      body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; margin: 30px; }
      label { display: block; margin-top: 12px; font-weight: bold; }
      input { width: 300px; padding: 8px; margin-top: 4px; }
      button { margin-top: 16px; padding: 10px 20px; cursor: pointer; }
      #status { margin-top: 16px; color: green; }
    </style>
  </head>
  <body>
    <h2>Replace Variable in Slides</h2>

    <label for="variable">Variable to find (e.g. {{name}})</label>
    <input type="text" id="variable" placeholder="{{name}}">

    <label for="replacement">Replace with</label>
    <input type="text" id="replacement" placeholder="Enter text...">

    <button onclick="submitForm()">Replace</button>

    <div id="status"></div>

    <script>
      function submitForm() {
        const data = {
          variable: document.getElementById('variable').value,
          replacement: document.getElementById('replacement').value
        };

        google.script.run
          .withSuccessHandler(function(message) {
            document.getElementById('status').innerText = message;
          })
          .withFailureHandler(function(error) {
            document.getElementById('status').style.color = 'red';
            document.getElementById('status').innerText = 'Error: ' + error.message;
          })
          .replaceVariables(data);
      }
    </script>
  </body>
</html>
```

### Step 3: Deploy

1. In the Apps Script editor, click **Deploy → New deployment**.
2. Select type: **Web app**.
3. Set **Execute as: Me** and **Who has access** as needed.
4. Click **Deploy** and authorize the permissions.
5. Open the provided URL to use your form.

---

## How to Find Your Presentation ID

Open your Slides file. The URL looks like:

```
https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/THIS_LONG_STRING_IS_THE_ID/edit
```

Copy the string between `/d/` and `/edit`.

---

## How It Works

- **Placeholders:** In your slides, type variables like `{{name}}`, `{{date}}`, or `{{company}}` anywhere you want text replaced.
- **`replaceAllText(find, replace)`:** Searches *all* slides, text boxes, tables, and notes, replacing every match at once.

---

## Notes & Tips

- Use a distinctive format like `{{variable}}` so you don't accidentally replace normal words.
- `replaceAllText` runs across the **entire presentation**, including notes and tables.
- To replace multiple variables at once, you could extend the form with more fields and loop through them.

---

