# EMG and GSR Averaging with Arduino Uno

Here's a sample code that reads from EMG and GSR sensors, collects 60 samples, and calculates the average:

## Basic Version

```cpp
// Pin definitions
const int EMG_PIN = A0;  // EMG sensor connected to analog pin A0
const int GSR_PIN = A1;  // GSR sensor connected to analog pin A1

const int NUM_SAMPLES = 60;  // Number of samples to average

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  Serial.println("EMG and GSR Averaging Started");
}

void loop() {
  long emgSum = 0;
  long gsrSum = 0;

  // Collect 60 samples
  for (int i = 0; i < NUM_SAMPLES; i++) {
    emgSum += analogRead(EMG_PIN);
    gsrSum += analogRead(GSR_PIN);
    delay(10);  // Small delay between readings
  }

  // Calculate averages
  float emgAverage = (float)emgSum / NUM_SAMPLES;
  float gsrAverage = (float)gsrSum / NUM_SAMPLES;

  // Display results
  Serial.print("EMG Average: ");
  Serial.print(emgAverage);
  Serial.print("\tGSR Average: ");
  Serial.println(gsrAverage);

  delay(1000);  // Wait 1 second before next batch
}
```

## Enhanced Version (with Voltage Conversion)

```cpp
const int EMG_PIN = A0;
const int GSR_PIN = A1;
const int NUM_SAMPLES = 60;

const float VREF = 5.0;        // Arduino reference voltage
const int ADC_RESOLUTION = 1024; // 10-bit ADC

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  Serial.println("=== EMG & GSR Sensor Reading ===");
}

void loop() {
  long emgSum = 0;
  long gsrSum = 0;

  // Collect samples
  for (int i = 0; i < NUM_SAMPLES; i++) {
    emgSum += analogRead(EMG_PIN);
    gsrSum += analogRead(GSR_PIN);
    delay(10);
  }

  // Calculate average raw values
  float emgRaw = (float)emgSum / NUM_SAMPLES;
  float gsrRaw = (float)gsrSum / NUM_SAMPLES;

  // Convert to voltage
  float emgVoltage = emgRaw * (VREF / ADC_RESOLUTION);
  float gsrVoltage = gsrRaw * (VREF / ADC_RESOLUTION);

  // Display results
  Serial.println("-------------------------");
  Serial.print("EMG Raw: ");
  Serial.print(emgRaw, 2);
  Serial.print(" | Voltage: ");
  Serial.print(emgVoltage, 3);
  Serial.println(" V");

  Serial.print("GSR Raw: ");
  Serial.print(gsrRaw, 2);
  Serial.print(" | Voltage: ");
  Serial.print(gsrVoltage, 3);
  Serial.println(" V");

  delay(1000);
}
```

## Key Points

| Component | Description |
|-----------|-------------|
| **EMG_PIN (A0)** | Reads muscle electrical activity |
| **GSR_PIN (A1)** | Reads skin conductance (sweat/stress) |
| **NUM_SAMPLES** | 60 readings to average |
| **long data type** | Prevents overflow when summing values |

## Wiring

```
EMG Sensor:  Signal → A0,  VCC → 5V,  GND → GND
GSR Sensor:  Signal → A1,  VCC → 5V,  GND → GND
```

## Tips

- **Adjust `delay(10)`** between samples based on your sampling rate needs (10ms = 100Hz sampling)
- **Use `long`** for the sum to avoid integer overflow (60 × 1023 = 61,380 which exceeds int max of 32,767)
- For **faster sampling**, reduce or remove the inner delay
- Consider adding a **moving average filter** if you need continuous smoothed readings

